&lt;h4 id=&quot;perks-of-using-jekyll-for-your-projects&quot;&gt;Perks of using Jekyll for your projects:&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;ul&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;No backend/databases&lt;/strong&gt; (yes, I consider this as a huge benefit, especially if you are just blogging)&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Static files&lt;/strong&gt;, all you need is html + css and sometimes some simple javascript logic (for slider f.ex.);&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Markdown&lt;/strong&gt; - it is easy to document and write posts&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Plugins&lt;/strong&gt; - jekyll has some awesome plugins for SEO, asset management and etc.&lt;/li&gt;
  &lt;li&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Hosting&lt;/strong&gt; - it is easy to host, even github pages can host jekyll website&lt;/li&gt;
&lt;/ul&gt;

&lt;h4 id=&quot;what-packages-and-tools-i-am-using&quot;&gt;What packages and tools I am using&lt;/h4&gt;

&lt;p&gt;For my blogs I usually reuse the same plugins, the most useful I found are these:&lt;/p&gt;

